description: Spring Beauty is one of our native spring ephemerals -- bulb plants that live under trees, and do their entire year's worth of growth before the tree canopy leafs out and steals their sun. Then they die back, & most of the year you wouldn't even know they're there. This one is very common at the edges of clearings, often seen volunteering in park lawns (that's where this patch was). It's only ~1 cm across. My new camera takes much better macros than my old one, plus the shot I got last year was taken on ISO 400, so I've been waiting a whole year to get a better shot of this gem.

description: Perennial herbaceous plant growing from heights of 4" to 12" arising from an underground corm. Stem leaves present as a singlet, or single opposite pair and extremely narrow often extending more than 3" in length, yet 0.2-1.2 cm in width. Leaf shape is linear to linear-lanceolate with indistinct petiole. Small, delicate terminal 5-petal flowers, with 5 noticeable extruding stamens and persistent calyxes. Flower color is often white (with pale pink venination), or pale pink (with further pink veination). Commonly found growing in rich woods, roadsides, and lawns in early spring and summer disappearing by midsummer.

The flower was common in the low grassy understory of a cedar elm-pecan woodland along Onion Creek in McKinney Falls SP.  Help!
